<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI - 8JAN97 - TROUBLE IN TAJIKISTAN'S "WILD WEST"</title>
<h1>OMRI - 8JAN97 - TROUBLE IN TAJIKISTAN'S "WILD WEST"</h1>
<i>ctroy@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 08 Jan 97 16:47:15 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#81">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#81">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#81">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#81">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0082.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 9JAN97 - FIGHTING BREAKS OUT IN TURSUN ZADE"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0080.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 8JAN97 - TROUBLE IN TAJIKISTAN'S "WILD WEST""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
          TAJIK BRIGADE COMMANDER DISOBEYS ORDER, CONTINUES FIGHTING<br>
          <br>
                         DUSHANBE, Jan  8 (Interfax)  - Makhmud Khudoberdiyev, <br>
          the commander of  a rapid  deployment brigade,  has  disobeyed  an <br>
          order to  withdraw from  Tursunzade by Tajik President Emomali<br>
          Rakhmonov,  the   supreme  commander   of  the  armed  forces,<br>
          presidential  press   secretary  Zafar  Saidov  told  Interfax<br>
          Wednesday.<br>
                Rakhmonov had demanded Khudoberdiyev withdraw his brigadefrom  <br>
          Tursunzade,  situated  54  kilometers  to  the  west  of Dushanbe, to  <br>
          its permanent  location in Kurgantyube by 4 p.m.Wednesday.<br>
                Due to  Khudoberdiyev's refusal  to obey  the order,  the <br>
          situation in  the western  part of  Tajikistan  remains  quite<br>
          tense, Saidov said.<br>
                However, an  Interfax correspondent has reported from thesuburbs <br>
           of   Tursunzade  that   Khudoberdiyev's  brigade  hadadvanced 12 more <br>
          kilometers to the west by 6 p.m. local time.       <br>
                Khudoberdiyev's brigade  and his  supporters  from  local <br>
          self-defense units  seized a  major  aluminum  plant  and  the<br>
          eastern suburbs  of Tursunzade, servicemen at outposts outside<br>
          the city told Interfax.<br>
                According to  some reports,  Khudoberdiyev  demanded  the <br>
          resignation of  the Tursunzade  mayor and  the  street  police<br>
          chief.<br>
                Earlier in  the morning,  Khudoberdiyev demanded that thelocal <br>
          gang  headed by  Kadyr Abdullayev  return arms seized in the city  on <br>
          December 29, 1996, and hand over the killers of a brigade officer.<br>
          Witnesses  reported   shoot-outs  in   the   suburbs   of<br>
          Tursunzade during  the day.  At least  four people  have  been<br>
          killed and more wounded, their exact number unknown.<br>
                The military  did not  let a  group of  Russian reporterswithin <br>
          15 kilometers of Tursunzade. The Tajik  leadership still  wants to <br>
          settle the conflict by way of negotiation, without using force, Saidov <br>
          said.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
