<!-- body="start" -->
                      TAJIK GROUP FREES REBEL MEMBER OF JOINT COMMISSION<br>
     <br>
                    DUSHANBE, Dec  26 (Interfax)  - A  Tajik armed  group  on<br>
               Wednesday evening  freed one  of the  two members of the Joint<br>
               Cease-fire Commission taken hostage on December 20.<br>
                    Izatullo Ibodzoda,  a representative  of the United Tajik<br>
               Opposition, was exchanged for the brother of the armed group's<br>
               commander Rizvon Sadirov, released by the supreme commander of<br>
     <br>
               the Tavildara  group of forces of the United Tajik Opposition,<br>
               Mirzo Zikeyev.<br>
                    Ibodzoda was taken by car to Dushanbe by a representative<br>
               of field commander Bakhrom, a spokesman for the Tajik Security<br>
               Council told  Interfax Thursday. However, the other opposition<br>
               representative in  the commission,  Yusuf Khakimov,  is  still<br>
               held hostage.<br>
                    The two officials were captured on a highway during their<br>
               trip to the district center of Garm situated 150 kilometers to<br>
               the  east   of  Dushanbe.  U.N.  military  observers  and  the<br>
               government  officials   who  accompanied  them  were  released<br>
               shortly after their capture.<br>
                    Khakimov's release  will continue  to  be  negotiated  on<br>
               December 27.<br>
                    Tajik Security  Council Secretary Amirkul Azimov plans to<br>
               fly to  Garm by  the end  of today  to continue  talks on  the<br>
               resumption of local authorities and Khakimov's release.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
