<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: Interfax 23Dec96, Tajik Govt &amp; Opposition Sign Moscow Accord</title>
<h1>Interfax 23Dec96, Tajik Govt &amp; Opposition Sign Moscow Accord</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Mon, 30 Dec 96 15:53:33 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#72">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#72">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#72">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#72">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0073.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax 26Dec96 Tajik Group Frees Joint Commission Member"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0071.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 19DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION FREES CAPTIVES; MOSCOW TAL"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     TAJIK PRESIDENT, OPPOSITION LEADER SIGN AGREEMENTS IN MOSCOW<br>
     <br>
                    MOSCOW, Dec  23  (Interfax)  -  Tajik  President  Emomali<br>
               Rakhmonov and  leader of  the United  Tajik  Opposition  Sayed<br>
               Abdullo Nuri  have signed  two documents which are expected to<br>
               end the fratricidal confrontation in Tajikistan. The documents<br>
               were signed  at Moscow's  President-Hotel in  the presence  of<br>
               Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.<br>
                    The sides  signed an  agreement between  the president of<br>
               Tajikistan and  the leader  of the  United Tajik Opposition on<br>
               the results  of the  Moscow summit,  and  a  protocol  on  the<br>
               functions  and   powers   of   the   National   Reconciliation<br>
               Commission.<br>
                    In  accordance   with  the   documents,  the  sides  have<br>
               committed themselves  to completing  the inter-Tajik  talks by<br>
               July 1  for the purpose of restoring peace in Tajikistan. They<br>
               are also  planning to  announce a general amnesty and exchange<br>
               prisoners of  war. In line with the protocol, this job will be<br>
               done by the National Reconciliation Commission during the next<br>
               12-18 months.<br>
                    The  protocol   says  that  the  National  Reconciliation<br>
               Commission shall  be set  up for  the transitional  period and<br>
               that its  functions will  be  defined  and  members  appointed<br>
     <br>
               during the next round of the inter-Tajik talks. The commission<br>
               is to  be led  by a  representative  of  the  opposition.  The<br>
               document fully corresponds to the Tajik Constitution.<br>
                    "Given the  beginning of a qualitatively new stage in the<br>
               work to  achieve peace  and national accord in Tajikistan, the<br>
               sides will  shape a National Reconciliation Commission for the<br>
               transitional period,"  says the  protocol, a copy of which was<br>
               made available to Interfax.<br>
                    "The main  task of  the commission is to achieve national<br>
               reconciliation by  implementing the  agreements reached during<br>
               the inter-Tajik  talks, by creating an atmosphere of trust and<br>
               mutual forgiveness, and by initiating a broad dialogue between<br>
               different political  forces for  the  sake  of  restoring  and<br>
               strengthening civic accord in Tajikistan," says the protocol.<br>
                    The protocol  confers the  following functions  upon  the<br>
               commission:<br>
                    - to  develop a  mechanism for and exercise monitoring of<br>
               the implementation  of the  peace and accord agreement by both<br>
               sides together with other bodies created for this purpose;<br>
                    - to  carry out  measures to  make possible  a  safe  and<br>
               dignified return  of refugees,  their active engagement in the<br>
               country's social,  political and economic life, to promote the<br>
               reconstruction  of   war-damaged   housing,   industrial   and<br>
               agricultural facilities;<br>
                    - to  develop proposals  on amending  laws  on  political<br>
               parties, movements and the mass media.<br>
                    The president  and the National Reconciliation Commission<br>
               will exercise  the following  functions and  powers during the<br>
               transitional period:<br>
                    - submit  proposals on amending the existing constitution<br>
               in a nationwide referendum;<br>
                    - prepare and submit a new law on parliamentary and local<br>
               elections  to  the  parliament  or,  if  need  be,  nationwide<br>
               referendum;<br>
                    - form the Central Election and Referendum Commission for<br>
               the transitional period;<br>
                    -   reform    the   government,    introduce   opposition<br>
               representatives to  executive  bodies,  including  ministries,<br>
               agencies, local  government bodies, courts and law-enforcement<br>
               bodies in proportion to the representation of the two sides in<br>
               the National  Reconciliation Commission  and  considering  the<br>
               regional principle;<br>
                    - direct  and supervise  the abolition,  disarmament  and<br>
               reintegration of  opposition units, reform law-enforcement and<br>
               prosecution bodies;<br>
                    - ensure all prisoners of war, convicted and hostages are<br>
               exchanged;<br>
                    - adopt  a law  on mutual  forgiveness, develop  a law on<br>
               amnesty, to  be approved  by the  parliament and  the National<br>
               Reconciliation Commission;<br>
                    - develop  a mechanism  for reforming  military-political<br>
               movements into political parties;<br>
                    - submit  proposals on  a date  for elections  of  a  new<br>
               professional parliament  for  consideration  by  the  existing<br>
               parliament,  under   U.N.   and   OSCE   auspices   and   with<br>
               participation of observers at the Tajik talks.<br>
                    "The decisions  made by  the president and the commission<br>
               on issues  of national  reconciliation  will  be  binding  for<br>
               organs of  power," reads  the protocol. "The activities by the<br>
     <br>
               National Reconciliation  Commission will  be  carried  out  in<br>
               close cooperation  with the U.N. observer mission and the OSCE<br>
               assistance group  in Tajikistan. The commission will cease its<br>
               activities after  a new  parliament and its leading bodies are<br>
               elected."<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
