<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI - 19DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION FREES CAPTIVES; MOSCOW TAL</title>
<h1>OMRI - 19DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION FREES CAPTIVES; MOSCOW TAL</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 19 Dec 96 13:02:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax 23Dec96, Tajik Govt &amp; Opposition Sign Moscow Accord"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - UN OBSERVERS IN TAJIKISTAN VICTIMS OF "MOCK"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     TAJIK OPPOSITION FREES CAPTIVES; MOSCOW TALKS DELAYED. The Tajik <br>
     opposition on 18 December released 39 hostages captured in recent <br>
     fighting, RFE/RL reported. Those freed were described only as "high- <br>
     ranking" officials. The move was agreed at a meeting of Tajik <br>
     President Imomali Rakhmonov and opposition leader Said Abdullo Nuri on <br>
     10-11 December. Talks between the two leaders in Moscow scheduled for <br>
     19 December have been pushed back a day as Nuri's departure was <br>
     delayed by an opposition meeting in Tehran on 18 December, according <br>
     to Russian sources. In a brief interview with Nezavisimaya gazeta on <br>
     19 December, Rakhmonov said that a national reconciliation council <br>
     must be set up but-a stipulation of the original cease-fire agreement <br>
     signed in Tehran in 1994-but added: "It's not our fault the agreement <br>
     has not been realized." * Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
