<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI - 18DEC96 - UN OBSERVERS IN TAJIKISTAN VICTIMS OF "MOCK</title>
<h1>OMRI - 18DEC96 - UN OBSERVERS IN TAJIKISTAN VICTIMS OF "MOCK</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 96 11:40:05 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 19DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION FREES CAPTIVES; MOSCOW TAL"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     UN OBSERVERS IN TAJIKISTAN VICTIMS OF "MOCK EXECUTION." Two teams of <br>
     UN observers in Tajikistan were stopped at a government checkpoint, <br>
     verbally and physically abused, and subject to forced to stand in a <br>
     line for a mock execution, according to an 18 December UN press <br>
     release. The teams were traveling to Garm to verify reports of <br>
     cease-fire violations in the area when they were stopped at the <br>
     Saripul post. Their communications equipment was confiscated and <br>
     members of the teams were ordered to line up in a field for execution. <br>
     Government soldiers then fired above and around the men. The UN team <br>
     was able to escape when the appearance of a car on the road diverted <br>
     the soldiers' attention. This is the second time this month that <br>
     government forces have mistreated UN observers. -- Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
