<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI - 16DEC96 - CEASE-FIRE TAKING HOLD IN TAJIKISTAN</title>
<h1>OMRI - 16DEC96 - CEASE-FIRE TAKING HOLD IN TAJIKISTAN</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Mon, 16 Dec 96 12:17:12 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#68">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#68">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#68">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#68">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0069.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0067.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax-13 Dec. Tajik Opposition Kills 4, Wounds 14 Troops"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     CEASE-FIRE TAKING HOLD IN TAJIKISTAN. The cease-fire agreement signed <br>
     at the conclusion of a 10-11 December meeting between Tajik President <br>
     Imomali Rakhmonov and opposition leader Said Abdullo Nuri appears to <br>
     be reducing fighting in central Tajikistan, according to international <br>
     sources. This latest agreement seemed doomed when less than 24 hours <br>
     after its signing two bombs went off in the Tajik capital and fighting <br>
     was reported in Garm. Four government soldiers were killed and 14 <br>
     wounded in the town on 13 December. However, by 15 December only <br>
     sporadic gunfire was reported near Garm, although a special unit of <br>
     government troops remains surrounded. AFP reported that a special <br>
     meeting was held on 13 December in Dushanbe attended by <br>
     representatives of the government, opposition, and UN special envoy <br>
     Gerd Merrem to prevent the cease-fire agreement from falling apart. -- <br>
     Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
