<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: Interfax-13 Dec. Tajik Opposition Kills 4, Wounds 14 Troops</title>
<h1>Interfax-13 Dec. Tajik Opposition Kills 4, Wounds 14 Troops</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 13 Dec 96 13:35:16 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 16DEC96 - CEASE-FIRE TAKING HOLD IN TAJIKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 13DEC96 - TAJIK CEASEFIRE VIOLATED IN FIRST 24 HOURS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
               TAJIK OPPOSITION KILLS FOUR, WOUNDS 14 GOVT TROOPS<br>
     <br>
                    DUSHANBE, Dec  13 (Interfax)  - Tajik  opposition  rebels<br>
               Friday  morning  continued  to  fire  on  the  Tajik  Interior<br>
               Ministry's special  battalion in  the settlement  of Garm some<br>
               150 kilometers east of the Tajik capital of Dushanbe.<br>
                    Early reports  say four government troops were killed and<br>
               another 14  wounded,  a  well-informed  source  in  the  Tajik<br>
               Interior Ministry told Interfax.<br>
                    No information  about  the  number  of  casualties  among<br>
               opposition troops was immediately available.<br>
                    The opposition  units, numbering  about 200  rebels,  had<br>
               also attacked  the government  force on  Thursday morning. The<br>
               attack  Friday   morning  involved  three  howitzers,  grenade<br>
               launchers and fire-arms.<br>
                    The  Tajik  government  Thursday  protested  against  the<br>
               violation of  the protocol  on the political settlement of the<br>
               situation in  the Karategin  and Tavildara areas. The protocol<br>
               was signed  by Tajik  President Emomali  Rakhmonov  and  Tajik<br>
               opposition leader  Said Abdullo  Nuri during  their meeting in<br>
               northern Afghanistan on December 11.<br>
                    The Tajik  government said  it retains  the right to take<br>
               measures  in  response  to  attacks  by  the  opposition.  The<br>
               opposition will  be responsible for all possible consequences,<br>
               the Tajik government said.<br>
                    "The government  is  still  ready  to  settle  the  armed<br>
               confrontation in  the Pamir  foothills by  peaceful  political<br>
               methods," the source in the Interior Ministry said.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
