<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI - 10DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION LEADER ARRIVES IN KUNDUZ</title>
<h1>OMRI - 10DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION LEADER ARRIVES IN KUNDUZ</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 10 Dec 96 11:04:15 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 11DEC96 - TAJIK PRESIDENT, OPPOSITION LEADER MEET"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 9DEC96 - TAJIK OPPOSITION LEADER'S PLANE FORCED DOWN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     TAJIK OPPOSITION LEADER ARRIVES IN KUNDUZ. United Tajik Opposition <br>
     leader Said Abdullo Nuri flew to Kunduz on 9 December, arriving one <br>
     day late for a scheduled meeting with Tajik President Imomali <br>
     Rakhmonov, international press reported. Details on Nuri's delay are <br>
     conflicting, with some reports claiming that Taliban aircraft forced <br>
     the plane down at Shindan then transferred it to Kandahar, while <br>
     others claiming that the plane had technical difficulties and <br>
     requested a landing for repairs. One thing is certain, Nuri did meet <br>
     with Taliban leader Mullah Mohammed Omar. -- Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
