<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: Interfax - 25 November - Tajik govt. retakes Sagirdasht</title>
<h1>Interfax - 25 November - Tajik govt. retakes Sagirdasht</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 26 Nov 96 18:23:21 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 26Nov96 - TAJIK PRESIDENT, OPPOSITION LEADER TO MEET"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 22Nov96 - Russian Commander in Tajikistan Demands Act"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
           TAJIK GOVT RETAKES TOWN WITH SUPPLY DEPOTS PLUNDERED BY REBELS<br>
     <br>
                    DUSHANBE, Nov  25 (Interfax)  - Tajik  government  <br>
     troops have regained control over the town of Sagirdasht, located 200 <br>
     kilometers to  the east of Dushanbe, a senior Defense Ministry<br>
     source told Interfax Monday.<br>
        Tajik rebels  had seized  the town  in  late  October  in<br>
     defiance  of  the  Tehran  cease-fire  agreement  between  the<br>
     government and the opposition, the source recalled.<br>
        Unlike  Tavildara   some  15  kilometers  to  the  north,<br>
     Sagirdasht does  not have  so much  strategic importance,  the<br>
     officer said.  However, the town had contained government food<br>
     and ammunition depots, he noted.<br>
     "This is  the only  reason why  Sagirdasht fell  into the<br>
     area of  military operations  and why  rebels fully robbed the<br>
     depots, taking  away food, clothes and ammunition," the source<br>
     said.<br>
        About 40  remaining rebels retreated from the city to the northwest <br>
     virtually  without  engagement  Sunday  evening,  he said.<br>
     "Government forces are gradually regaining control in the<br>
     Tavildara  area,   and,  what   is  noteworthy,  with  minimum<br>
     casualties," the  officer said  in comment on the situation in<br>
     the area.<br>
        "The  Defense  Ministry  does  not  have  information  on <br>
     casualties among opposition militia," he said. "Life is  returning to  <br>
     normal" in  Sagirdasht and  other areas, the  source said.  "Local <br>
     authorities,  which have been idle over the last month, are being <br>
     restored," he said.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
