<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: INTERFAX--12 NOV--TAJIK PRESIDENT LIKELY TO MAKE CONCESSIONS</title>
<h1>INTERFAX--12 NOV--TAJIK PRESIDENT LIKELY TO MAKE CONCESSIONS</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 12 Nov 96 17:45:12 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#50">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#50">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#50">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#50">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0051.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18Nov96 - Komsomolabad Falls to Tajik Opposition"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0049.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "INTERFAX-12 NOV 96--CONTINUED CONFLICT WILL SPLIT TAJIKISTAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 TAJIK PRESIDENT LIKELY TO MAKE CONCESSIONS TO OPPOSITION<br>
<p>
               MOSCOW, Nov  12  (Interfax)  -  Tajik  President  Imamali<br>
          Rakhmonov  is   likely  to  make  concessions  to  the  allied<br>
          opposition, sources  in the  Tajikistan  National  Renaissance<br>
          Movement told Interfax Tuesday.<br>
               Former prime minister Abdumalik Abdulladzhanov chairs the<br>
          movement,  Jamshed  Khilolov  and  Abdudzhalil  Samadov,  also<br>
          former prime ministers, being his deputies.<br>
<p>
               Rakhmonov's staff  has developed a draft agreement, which<br>
          may be  signed at  his planned  meeting with  Tajik opposition<br>
          leader Said  Abdullo Nuri  in Moscow  by the  end of 1996, the<br>
          sources said.<br>
               In part,  the draft  document stipulates  that "the talks<br>
          and the  implementation of the agreements to be reached are to<br>
          be accomplished within 12 to 18 months after this agreement is<br>
          signed," they said.<br>
               "The Tajik president and the opposition leader are making<br>
          a decision  to create a commission for national reconciliation<br>
          for the above-indicated transitional period, which would enjoy<br>
          wide-spread powers,  including  executive  functions,  on  all<br>
          issues concerning  the establishment  of  peace  and  national<br>
          accord in  the country,  chiefly  on  political  and  military<br>
          issues," the draft agreement reads.<br>
               The commission  will be formed according to the principle<br>
          of "justice,  considering the  interests of  all political and<br>
          social  forces  in  the  republic,"  the  document  reads.  An<br>
          opposition representative will head the commission.<br>
               The functions  and powers of the current legislature will<br>
          be delegated  to the  president and  the commission before new<br>
          elections.<br>
               The commission  will develop  amendments and additions to<br>
          the existing  constitution and  draft  laws,  particularly  on<br>
          political  parties   and  public   associations,  mass  media,<br>
          parliamentary and presidential elections.<br>
               The  draft   agreement  also   provides  for  creating  a<br>
          government   of    national   accord   with   a   proportional<br>
          representation of  various political  parties  and  movements,<br>
          considering regional division, "especially with respect to the<br>
          power ministries and administrative bodies."<br>
               The draft  document will  declare an  amnesty "and mutual<br>
          pardon  to  all  people  engaged  in  military  and  political<br>
          confrontation since  1992 until the moment this amnesty act is<br>
          approved."<br>
               The Tajik  authorities may  still "slightly  adjust"  the<br>
          document, the sources told Interfax.<br>
               "In  this   case,  any   amendments  will   have  to   be<br>
          preliminarily  agreed  on  with  the  leaders  of  the  allied<br>
          opposition," they said.<br>
               Interfax has  not  received  confirmation  that  a  draft<br>
          agreement with the opposition has been developed in Dushanbe.<br>
<p>
(c) Interfax, 1996<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
