<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: INTERFAX-12 NOV 96--CONTINUED CONFLICT WILL SPLIT TAJIKISTAN</title>
<h1>INTERFAX-12 NOV 96--CONTINUED CONFLICT WILL SPLIT TAJIKISTAN</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 12 Nov 96 17:44:02 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "INTERFAX--12 NOV--TAJIK PRESIDENT LIKELY TO MAKE CONCESSIONS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax-11 Nov--INTER-TAJIK SETTLEMENT DISCUSSED IN MOSCOW"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
 <br>
           CONTINUATION OF CONFLICT WILL SPLIT TAJIKISTAN, MODERATE SAYS<br>
 <br>
                MOSCOW, Nov  12 (Interfax)  - "The  continuation  of  the<br>
           conflict in  Tajikistan will  split the country," according to<br>
           the National Renewal Movement leader Abdumalik Abdullajanov.<br>
                In an  exclusive interview  with  Interfax  the  moderate<br>
           opposition figure  said: "It  may happen  so that  the country<br>
           will be  divided into independent northern and southern areas.<br>
           It  is  clear  even  today  that  the  Tajik  authorities  and<br>
           President Emomali  Rakhmonov have  practically no control over<br>
           Gorno Badakhshan  or the  Tavildara zone  held mainly  by  the<br>
           armed opposition."<br>
                The former  prime minister  sharply criticized Rakhmonov.<br>
           "He and  his supporters  are obsessed  with keeping  power  in<br>
           their hands.  They are absolutely unmoved by the future of the<br>
           country or people," he said.<br>
                Describing the  key principles  of his movement's program<br>
           Abdullajanov said  a special  body - a national reconciliation<br>
           commission - should be set up for the transitional period with<br>
           broad power and executive functions on political matters.<br>
                He said the commission would be formed by an equal number<br>
           of representatives from every region.<br>
                During the  transitional  period  the  functions  of  the<br>
           parliament  would  be  performed  by  the  president  and  the<br>
           national reconciliation commission, Abdullajanov said.<br>
                A coalition  government  of  all  political  parties  and<br>
           public movements would be formed during the period.<br>
                The opposition  figure  described  the  current  economic<br>
           situation in the country as disastrous.<br>
                "The economy  is at  a standstill, people live in poverty<br>
           while the  leadership that  seized power by force is cynically<br>
           squandering the country," he said.<br>
                If the  situation does  not change  for the better, which<br>
           Abdullajanov strongly  doubted, he predicted a social outburst<br>
           in one or two years at the most.<br>
                He is  convinced "Rakhmonov  must reach a compromise with<br>
           the armed  opposition" and is absolutely sure no stability can<br>
           be reached without it.<br>
                "Sooner or  later, by  his own  free will  or  under  the<br>
           pressure of  circumstances President  Rakhmonov will  have  to<br>
           make concessions.  The sooner this happens, the better it will<br>
           be for the republic," Abdullajanov said.<br>
 <br>
          (C) Interfax, 1996<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
