<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: CIS Reaction to Afghan Events</title>
<h1>CIS Reaction to Afghan Events</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 01 Oct 96 13:00:53 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI-- 100296--TAJIKISTAN IMPACTED BY TURMOIL IN AFGHANISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--1 October 1996 -CENTRAL ASIA VOICES CONCERN OVER KABUL"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DUSHANBE, October 1 (Itar-Tass) -- The latest aggravation of the situation<br>
on the Tajik-Afghan border and the developments ensuing from the Taliban<br>
militia's seizure of Kabul and further advances towards northern Afghanistan<br>
and its borders with Tajikistan were discussed at a meeting between Tajik<br>
President Emomali Rakhmonov and commander of the CIS collective peacekeeping<br>
forces general Viktor Zavarzin here today, informed sources told Itar-Tass<br>
on Tuesday.<br>
   A spokesman for the command of the CIS collective peacekeeping forces<br>
subsequently told Itar-Tass that the command was seriously concerned over<br>
the mounting tension in the border area. He said that in view of the growing<br>
tension in the area and in keeping with its mandate, the CIS collective<br>
peacekeeping forces were prepared to give all necessary support to the<br>
Russian border troops deployed there, if threat to peace and stability kept<br>
mounting.<br>
   Military sources points in particular to the situation in the Kalaikhum<br>
sector of the border, where the Afghanistan-based Tajik rebels had been<br>
increasingly more active lately, launching repeated attempts at forcing<br>
their way into Tajikistan for almost a week and opening fire at anything<br>
moving on the other side of the border. Four Russian border troops and<br>
pilots have died and four have been wounded in gunfire exchanges with the<br>
Tajik opposition militants stationed in the Afghan territory adjacent on the<br>
Kalaikhum sector of the Tajik-Afghan border, the sources told Itar-Tass. One<br>
group of militants made its way into Tajikistan on September 27 and has<br>
since been attacking motor vehicles on the roads of the Kalaikhum area. The<br>
militants have taken five hostages, including a driver who was in service<br>
with the Russian border troops under a contract.<br>
   In the same area, two Russian crew died of wounds sustained when their<br>
combat helicopter came under fire from the territory of Afghanistan at the<br>
Kalaikhum section of the Tajik-Afghan border on Sunday. Captains Igor Budai<br>
and Valery Stovba were wounded and the helicopter was dangerously damaged by<br>
fire from an anti-aircraft machine-gun and small arms when it was on a<br>
reconnaissance mission over the border. The crew commander succeeded in<br>
bringing the helicopter safely to land at the base but the two men's wounds<br>
proved to be fatal.<br>
   All this called for adequate response on the part of the Russian border<br>
troops and the CIS collective peacekeeping forces.<br>
   In this context the latest developments in Afghanistan were seen as<br>
increasingly disturbing, according to the spokesman who said it was not<br>
ruled out that the hostilities between the Taleban militia and the Afghan<br>
government forces could spread as far as Tajikistan's northern borders<br>
further aggravating the situation there.<br>
   Concerted efforts on the part of all parties concerned, including the<br>
international community and the leading nations of the world, are needed to<br>
ensure peace and stability in the region, the spokesman said. The call for<br>
peace talks should come from the United Nations and it must be backed by the<br>
leading states of the world and the troubled region, including Tajikistan,<br>
the spokesman said.<br>
   For their part, the Tajik government and its power ministries were doing<br>
everything in their power to counter efforts aiming to disrupt progress<br>
towards the settlement, including vicious allegations and propaganda ploys<br>
on the part of the forces opposed to the settlement.<br>
   Tajik opposition forces in Afghan territory were clearly preparing to<br>
step up their activity, including in retaliation for the alleged bombardment<br>
of their positions by Tajik government planes.<br>
   Thus, Tajikistan's Defense Ministry categorically denied media reports<br>
alleging that its warplanes had bombarded the villages of Guram and<br>
Dashti-Sher in the mountainous Tavildara region and said in a statement<br>
released here today that the forces opposed to peace and stability in<br>
Tajikistan were indisputably behind the allegations about ar strikes.<br>
   The Ministry declared that the Tajik army's air wing had made no combat<br>
sorties since September 13, and no unidentified planes had been observed<br>
flying over the region.<br>
   The Defense Ministry said it fully backed all efforts to settle the<br>
Tajik-Tajik conflict and had taken part in the preceding truce negotiations<br>
between the Tajik government and the armed opposition in the Garm region for<br>
the purpose.<br>
   The Ministry welcomed the first signs of the political settlement in the<br>
Pamir mountain region of Tavildara as it had contributed jointly with the<br>
leaders of Tajikistan's other power ministries to the achievement of a<br>
ceasefire agreement with rebel commander Mirzo Zieyev.<br>
   Under the accord, ceasefire will be observed in the Tavildara region<br>
ahead of the beginning of the peace talks due to open on October 3 and<br>
expected to yield a truce protocol similar to that signed during the Garm<br>
talks to provide leeway for Tajik-Tajik settlement dialogue.<br>
   vfp/<br>
    Copyright 1996<br>
