<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI--9 September 96--TAJIK OPPOSITION SEIZES DJIR-GATAL</title>
<h1>OMRI--9 September 96--TAJIK OPPOSITION SEIZES DJIR-GATAL</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 10 Sep 96 07:38:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#19">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#19">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#19">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#19">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0020.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--9 September 96--TAJIK PRESIDENT SPEAKS ON ISLAM"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0018.html">eurasia@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI--30 August 1996--Border Guard Officers Confer"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     TAJIK OPPOSITION SEIZES DJIR-GATAL. Rebel units led by a commander <br>
     identified only as Akhmadbek on 7 September seized the town of <br>
     Djirgatal, 280 km northeast of Dushanbe, and killed two Tajik militia <br>
     members, Russian and Western agencies reported. The operation appears <br>
     to have been staged to coincide with the republic's fifth anniversary <br>
     of independence on 9 September. The 300-400 rebels disarmed and <br>
     expelled 46 Tajik militiamen to Kyrgyzstan across the border. The UN <br>
     envoy in Tajikistan, Gerd Merrem, issued a letter of protest on 8 <br>
     September urging an immediate cessation of hostilities in accordance <br>
     with the existing ceasefire agreement. -- Lowell Bezanis<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
