<!-- body="start" -->
     RUSSIA, TAJIKISTAN GIVEN OBSERVER STATUS IN CENTRAL ASIAN UNION. The <br>
     presidents of Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, and Uzbekistan met in Almaty on <br>
     23 August to discuss the formation of a common economic space, <br>
     ITAR-TASS and RFE/RL reported. The three signed agreements approving <br>
     the program for 1996-1997 and amending constituent documents of the <br>
     Central Asian Bank for Cooperation and Development (CABCD), which was <br>
     established in 1994. One of the agreements envisions the creation of a <br>
     single economic space among the three countries by 1998. Uzbekistan <br>
     consented to giving the CABCD access to its domestic market in order <br>
     to facilitate operations in Uzbek currency. At the same meeting, <br>
     Russia and Tajikistan were granted observer status in the Central <br>
     Asian Union. -- Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
