<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI -- 27 August 1996 -- ATTACK REPORTED 100 KM FROM DUSHAN</title>
<h1>OMRI -- 27 August 1996 -- ATTACK REPORTED 100 KM FROM DUSHAN</h1>
<i>eurasia@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 27 Aug 96 20:18:24 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#14">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#14">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#14">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#14">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0015.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--KILLERS OF TAJIK JOURNALIST RECEIVE DEAT"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0013.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "26 August 1996 -- OMRI -- Tajikistan's Neighbors Worried"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     ATTACK REPORTED 100 KM FROM DUSHANBE. A convoy of Tajik government <br>
     soldiers was ambushed on the road leading to the Tavil-Dara area on 24 <br>
     August, ITAR-TASS reported. One soldier was killed and four wounded <br>
     when elements of the Tajik opposition opened fire on the convoy near <br>
     the town of Chorsada, 100 kilometers northeast of the capital <br>
     Dushanbe. The Russian newspaper Krasnaya Zvezda speculated in its 23 <br>
     August issue that the opposition is attempting to gain control over <br>
     the mountainous regions of Tajikistan and split the country. <br>
     Meanwhile, on the diplomatic front, the opposition's Radio Voice of <br>
     Free Tajikistan dismissed an offer last week by Tajik Foreign Minister <br>
     Talbak Nazarov to include members of the opposition in the government. <br>
     "Such statements by the leaders of the regime are made on the advice <br>
     of Moscow," the radio said. -- Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0015.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--28 August 96--KILLERS OF TAJIK JOURNALIST RECEIVE DEAT"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0013.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "26 August 1996 -- OMRI -- Tajikistan's Neighbors Worried"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
