<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: 16 August 96 - Tajikistan: Clashes Reported Between Rival Militias</title>
<h1>16 August 96 - Tajikistan: Clashes Reported Between Rival Militias</h1>
<i>arichter@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Sat, 17 Aug 96 15:18:53 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--20 August 96--TAVIL-DARA IN OPPOSITION HANDS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "16 August 96 - Russian Soldier Killed, Two Wounded in Tajikistan"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     Tajikistan: Clashes Reported Between Rival Militias<br>
     <br>
     Dushanbe, 16 August 1996 (RFE/RL) - Recurring clashes between rival <br>
     militias have been reported in western Tajikistan. <br>
     <br>
     RFE/RL's Tajikistan Broadcast Service has received reports this week <br>
     of armed clashes and hostage-taking from that region. <br>
     <br>
     One of the focal points of the clashes is Tursunzade, one of the sites <br>
     of recent rebellions by local militia leaders against the government. <br>
     The<br>
     government fulfilled several demands of rebellion leaders, including <br>
     changes in the government, and named one of the rebellion leaders,<br>
     Habib Nasrulloen, to a top government post. <br>
     <br>
     Two of Nasrulloen's sons were reported to be among those kidnapped and <br>
     held for ransom this week. But they were freed by government<br>
     security forces. <br>
     <br>
     Authorities in Dushanbe have been meeting this week to try to ease <br>
     tensions in western Tajikistan. <br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
