<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: 16 August 96 - Russian Soldier Killed, Two Wounded in Tajikistan</title>
<h1>16 August 96 - Russian Soldier Killed, Two Wounded in Tajikistan</h1>
<i>arichter@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 16 Aug 96 18:59:36 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "16 August 96 - Tajikistan: Clashes Reported Between Rival Militias"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI ECON.DIGEST--15 August 96--IMF SATISFIED WITH REFORMS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     Russian Soldier Killed, Two Wounded in Tajikistan <br>
     <br>
        MOSCOW -- A Russian servicemen died and eight people were injured <br>
     in two bomb explosions in the Tajik capital Dushanbe on Thursday, <br>
     Interfax news agency said. It quoted the press office of the Russian <br>
     border guard force in Dushanbe as saying the first blast destroyed a <br>
     military truck carrying 12 servicemen to  work, killing one of them <br>
     and wounding two more. A Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman strongly <br>
     condemned the attack, and said it reflects the unstable situation in <br>
     the country, reported RIA news agency. Another explosion at about 1:00 <br>
     p.m. in a central cafe injured six people, two of them seriously. RIA <br>
     reported that the building was less than 100 meters (yards) from the <br>
     Tajikistan government building. It was not clear whether the blasts <br>
     were connected and no one has claimed responsibility. Interfax said <br>
     the first blast was caused by a remote-controlled explosive device <br>
     equivalent to 1 kilogram (2.5 pounds) of TNT.<br>
     <br>
        Under an intergovernmental agreement, Russia helps guard the uneasy <br>
     border between Tajikistan and Afghanistan, where Tajikistan's Islamic <br>
     opposition took refuge after defeat in a bloody civil war in 1992. <br>
     Dozens of Russian border guards in Dushanbe have been killed and in <br>
     attacks believed to have been staged by the rebels. None of the <br>
     attacks has been investigated and Moscow has criticized the Dushanbe <br>
     government for its inability to protect the Russian servicemen. <br>
     (Reuters, RIA Novosti) <br>
     <br>
     Source: Russia Today<br>
     &lt;<a href="http://www.ceo.cz/rtoday/rthome.html">http://www.ceo.cz/rtoday/rthome.html</a>&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
