<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Tajikistan: OMRI ECON.DIGEST--15 August 96--IMF SATISFIED WITH REFORMS</title>
<h1>OMRI ECON.DIGEST--15 August 96--IMF SATISFIED WITH REFORMS</h1>
<i>tlankina@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Fri, 16 Aug 96 13:42:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "16 August 96 - Russian Soldier Killed, Two Wounded in Tajikistan"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "Central Asia Monitor, Issue No. 3"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     . . . AND TAJIKISTAN. The head of the IMF mission to Tajikistan, Peter <br>
     Keller, said on 13 August that the IMF is satisfied with the course of <br>
     economic reforms in the Central Asian country, ITAR-TASS and RFE/RL <br>
     reported. Having reviewed Tajikistan's progress in the first seven <br>
     months of 1996, Keller pointed to the decline in inflation (0.5% in <br>
     May) and stable rate of the Tajik ruble against the dollar as signs of <br>
     improvement in Tajikistan's economy. Keller also noted that Tajikistan <br>
     has been adhering to the IMF's debt-servicing recommendations. The IMF <br>
     representative said the favorable economic climate in Tajikistan will <br>
     make it possible for the IMF to back the country when the issue of a <br>
     preferential credit worth $50 million comes up at a meeting of the <br>
     World Bank's council of directors on 12 September. -- Bruce Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
