<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: Interfax 31Dec96 Uzbek-Japanese agreements for textile prod.</title>
<h1>Interfax 31Dec96 Uzbek-Japanese agreements for textile prod.</h1>
<i>ctroy@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 08 Jan 97 16:49:36 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 9JAN97 - UZBEK GAS-CHEMICALS COMPLEX"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 8JAN97 - LAW ON POLITICAL PARTIES IN UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     JAPANESE FIRMS SIGN UP WITH UZBEKISTAN FOR TEXTILE PROJECTS<br>
     <br>
     TASHKENT, Dec  31 (Interfax) - Japan's Marubeni firm will<br>
     carry out  a turnkey  upgrade project  for Uzbekistan's  major textile <br>
     company  -  the  Fergana  textile  complex,  a  senior representative  <br>
     of    the   Uzbeklegprom   textile   industry association told <br>
     Interfax.<br>
        The textile  complex, located  in Fergana region, will be<br>
     upgraded  in  line  with  a  corresponding  agreement  between <br>
     Uzbeklegprom and  Marubeni signed  during a  Uzbek  government <br>
     delegation's recent  visit to Japan, Arkady Popovsky said. The Uzbek <br>
     delegation was led by Prime Minister Utkir Sultanov.<br>
     The project  envisages upgrading the spinning and weaving<br>
     sections  of   the  Fergana  textile  complex.  The  complex's <br>
     capacity will rise 1.5-fold to 9,500 tonnes of cotton yarn and 30 <br>
     million running meters of raw fabric annually.<br>
     The Uzbek  side estimates  the project's preliminary cost<br>
     at $80  million. The  project will  be financed  out of a loan from <br>
     Japan's  EX-IM Bank,  which will  cover some  85% of  the project's <br>
     cost, and Marubeni's loan which will cover about 15% of expenses.<br>
     In Japan,  the Uzbeklegprom  association  also  signed  a<br>
     protocol of  intent to  create two textile joint ventures with Japan's <br>
     Mitsubishi.  The  projects  between  Uzbeklegprom  and Mitsubishi cost <br>
     a total  of about  $100 million.  A tentative agreement has been <br>
     reached that the Uzbek side will have a 49% stake in  both ventures. <br>
     Besides Mitsubishi, the two ventures' foreign founders will also <br>
     include Turkey's Bursel.<br>
        Investments in  Uzbekistan's light  industry are  rising,<br>
     Uzbeklegprom said.  Early estimates say investments will reach $290 <br>
     million  in 1996-1997  compared with $30 million in 1995. Uzbeklegprom <br>
     enterprises  will be  able to export $250 million worth of products in <br>
     1998 compared with $13 million in 1995.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
