<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: OMRI - 30DEC96 - UN WORKERS TAKEN HOSTAGE IN TAJIKISTAN</title>
<h1>OMRI - 30DEC96 - UN WORKERS TAKEN HOSTAGE IN TAJIKISTAN</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Mon, 06 Jan 97 14:38:37 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 30DEC96 - KYRGYZ PRESIDENT IN UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 31DEC96 - UZBEK PARLIAMENT ADOPTS 1997 BUDGET"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     UN WORKERS TAKEN HOSTAGE IN TAJIKISTAN. A group led by Rezvon Sadirov <br>
     freed sixteen hostages within 24 hours of taking them after their <br>
     demands were met on 21 December, Western and Russian press reported. <br>
     Sadirov had threatened to kill the hostages, including seven UN <br>
     observers, unless his brother and others held by the opposition were <br>
     released. He also claimed his group had planted 30 bombs in Dushanbe, <br>
     the capital, and would explode them if his demands were not met. <br>
     Sadirov, a former defense minister for the Tajik opposition, was <br>
     demoted in 1995 and joined government forces last month. -- Bruce <br>
     Pannier<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
