<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: Interfax 27Dec96 Uzbek President Sums up 96 Econ. Results</title>
<h1>Interfax 27Dec96 Uzbek President Sums up 96 Econ. Results</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Mon, 30 Dec 96 16:44:52 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 31DEC96 - UZBEK PARLIAMENT ADOPTS 1997 BUDGET"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax 25Dec96 Uzbek Pres. Opposes CIS counter-NATO allian"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     UZBEK PRESIDENT SUMS UP ECONOMIC RESULTS OF 1996<br>
     <br>
     TASHKENT, Dec  27 (Interfax)  - The annual inflation rate<br>
     in Uzbekistan  totalled 60%  in 1996,  Uzbek  President  Islam Karimov <br>
     told diplomats and journalists in Tashkent Friday.<br>
     Karimov hoped  that next  year inflation  would be  below<br>
     27%. He  estimated investments in the Uzbek economy in 1996 at $6 <br>
     billion.<br>
        Industrial  output   rose  by  6%,  while  foreign  trade<br>
     turnover stood  at $8.3  billion, 40%  higher than in 1995, he said. <br>
     The  country harvested 3.45 million tonnes of raw cotton this year, he <br>
     said.<br>
        As much  as 47%  of  budget  revenue  in  1996  was  made<br>
     available  for  social  programs,  while  only  4.3%  went  on <br>
     defense, Karimov said.<br>
        Expenditures on  state  machinery  will  be  cut  by  20%<br>
     starting next year to make more funds available, he said.<br>
     Uzbekistan produced over 60 tonnes of gold in 1996, while<br>
     its gold  and hard  currency reserves  grew to  $1.5  billion, Karimov <br>
     told Interfax.<br>
        Next year  Uzbekistan plans to raise gold output further,<br>
     for which  works are  under way  in the  Pritashkent  district <br>
     together with  Japan's Mitsui  and the  United States' Newmont Mining.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
