<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: Interfax 25Dec96 Uzbek Pres. Opposes CIS counter-NATO allian</title>
<h1>Interfax 25Dec96 Uzbek Pres. Opposes CIS counter-NATO allian</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Mon, 30 Dec 96 15:56:47 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "Interfax 27Dec96 Uzbek President Sums up 96 Econ. Results"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 20DEC96 - IMF SUSPENDS LOAN TO UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
               UZBEK PRESIDENT OPPOSES CIS ALLIANCE AS COUNTERWEIGHT TO NATO<br>
     <br>
                    TASHKENT, Dec  25  (Interfax)  -  Uzbek  President  Islam<br>
               Karimov has  rejected the  idea of  the setting  up of  a  CIS<br>
               military-political  alliance  as  a  counterweight  to  NATO's<br>
               expansion eastwards.<br>
                    The CIS  should develop  through  bilateral  cooperations<br>
               like that between Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan, he said at a news<br>
               conference in  Tashkent at  the end  of Kyrgyz President Askar<br>
               Akayev's visit to Uzbekistan.<br>
                    "Of the  over 600 agreements signed in the CIS framework,<br>
               far from all work," he said.<br>
                    Karimov said  that he  and  Akayev  had  signed  numerous<br>
               documents, in  particular a  Treaty on  Eternal Friendship and<br>
               Cooperation. Akayev said that the word Eternal was inserted on<br>
               Karimov's initiative.<br>
                    The military  cooperation treaty  confirms the commitment<br>
               of the  two countries to the U.N. and OSCE charters and states<br>
     <br>
               that Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan do not intend to join alliances<br>
               hostile to  third  countries  or  to  make  their  territories<br>
               available for aggression against third countries.<br>
                    Akayev described  the free trade treaty signed by the two<br>
               countries as a very important document.<br>
                    Volume  of   trade  between   Uzbekistan  and  Kyrgyzstan<br>
               increased by  50% in 1995 and then doubled in 1996. It totaled<br>
               $200 million in the first nine months of 1996.<br>
                    Contrary to  expectations, the two countries did not sign<br>
               an agreement  on increased  supplies of  Uzbek natural  gas to<br>
               Kyrgyzstan at preferential prices.<br>
                    Kyrgyzstan needs 1.15 billion cubic meters of Uzbek gas a<br>
               year. It  purchases most  of the  gas at  $65 for  1,000 cubic<br>
               meters. Kyrgyzstan  hoped to  get 500  million cubic meters of<br>
               Uzbek gas  for its  heating stations  at $50  for 1,000  cubic<br>
               meters in 1997.<br>
     <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
