<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: Interfax 12/18 Gold Joint Venture to Raise $188 mln for Uzbe</title>
<h1>Interfax 12/18 Gold Joint Venture to Raise $188 mln for Uzbe</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 18 Dec 96 16:50:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 20DEC96 - IMF SUSPENDS LOAN TO UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     JOINT VENTURE TO RAISE $188 MLN FOR UZBEKISTAN GOLD PROJECTS<br>
     <br>
                    TASHKENT, Dec  16 (Interfax)  - Angren  Gold  Company,  a<br>
               joint venture  between Uzbekistan,  Newmont Corporation of the<br>
               United States  and Mitsui  of Japan, will pump an initial $188<br>
               million into the development of the Kyzylalmasai and Kochbulak<br>
               gold fields,  Tulkun Shayakubov,  head of  the country's State<br>
               Committee for Geology and Subsurface Resources, told Interfax.<br>
                    Shayakubov said $105 million of the total would be raised<br>
               in foreign bank credit.<br>
                    Newmont and  Mitsui in  May 1996  won a tender to develop<br>
               the two  goldfields in  Tashkent  region,  which  the  geology<br>
               committee estimates  contain an  overall 270  tonnes of  gold,<br>
               with average ore grades of 6-8 grams/tonne.<br>
                    The agreement  to form  the joint  venture was  signed on<br>
               October 2  this year.  Shayakubov said  Newmont and Mitsui own<br>
               respective stakes of 40% and 20%.<br>
                    The geology  committee and  Uzalmazzoloto, a  major Uzbek<br>
               gold  mining   association,  own  a  combined  stake  of  40%.<br>
               Shayakubov said  this was  the first time the Uzbek government<br>
               had agreed  to a  smaller stake  and participatory  share than<br>
               western partners in a gold mining project.<br>
                    Angren Gold Company will probably have an initial charter<br>
               capital of  $20 million,  to be  spent mainly on a feasibility<br>
               study for the Kyzylalmasai and Kochbulak project. The venture,<br>
               by initial  estimates, could  produce 12  tonnes-15 tonnes  of<br>
               gold annually  (for more  details see Interfax Mining &amp; Metals<br>
               Report No. 51-52).<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
