<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: OMRI - 17DEC96 - ANOTHER POLITICAL CASUALTY IN UZBEKISTAN</title>
<h1>OMRI - 17DEC96 - ANOTHER POLITICAL CASUALTY IN UZBEKISTAN</h1>
<i>fsu@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 17 Dec 96 13:02:53 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 11DEC96 - UZBEKISTAN TO BUY RUSSIAN GRAIN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     ANOTHER POLITICAL CASUALTY IN UZBEKISTAN. The regional governor of the <br>
     Bukhara region, Mavlon Rahmonov, asked to be relieved of his duties on <br>
     14 December, Uzbek Radio reported. Current Deputy Finance Minister <br>
     Samoiddin Husinov, has been nominated by President Islam Karimov to <br>
     replace Rahmonov, who is the fourth regional governor to lose his job <br>
     this year. Poor harvest figures were cited as the reason for <br>
     Rahmonov's departure. While still incomplete, figures on Uzbekistan's <br>
     grain harvest reveal that, on average, less than 80% of the expected <br>
     quota was attained. Poor weather and mismanagement at the regional <br>
     level have been blamed for the shortfall. And, as in 1995, the result <br>
     has been a reshuffling of key positions in the government. -- Roger <br>
     Kangas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 18DEC96 - FREEDOM HOUSE REPORT NOTES LACK OF HUMAN RI"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 11DEC96 - UZBEKISTAN TO BUY RUSSIAN GRAIN"</a>
