<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: OMRI - 11DEC96 - UZBEKISTAN TO BUY RUSSIAN GRAIN</title>
<h1>OMRI - 11DEC96 - UZBEKISTAN TO BUY RUSSIAN GRAIN</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 11 Dec 96 11:16:00 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 17DEC96 - ANOTHER POLITICAL CASUALTY IN UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI - 3DEC96 - UZBEK HISTORIOGRAPHY"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     UZBEKISTAN TO BUY RUSSIAN GRAIN. Due to a poor 1996 harvest, <br>
     Uzbekistan agreed to exchange 100,000 metric tons of grain from Russia <br>
     in return for 18,200 tons of cotton, the BBC reported on 9 December. <br>
     The agreement is backed by a $27 million guarantee from European <br>
     bankers. Officials noted that Uzbekistan will have to make further <br>
     grain imports, as the 2.7 million ton harvest fell short of the 4.5 <br>
     million tons the country requires. -- Roger Kangas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">fsu@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI - 17DEC96 - ANOTHER POLITICAL CASUALTY IN UZBEKISTAN"</a>
