<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: OMRI--22 Oct 1996-TAMERLANE CELEBRATION BEGINS IN UZBEKISTAN</title>
<h1>OMRI--22 Oct 1996-TAMERLANE CELEBRATION BEGINS IN UZBEKISTAN</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Tue, 22 Oct 96 12:08:33 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#40">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#40">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#40">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#40">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0041.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--22 Oct 1996--LEADERS OF TURKIC-SPEAKING COUNTRIES MEET"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0039.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "OMRI--21 Oct 1996--PAKISTAN'S PRESIDENT VISITS UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     <br>
     TAMERLANE CELEBRATION BEGINS IN UZBEKISTAN. The much-anticipated <br>
     celebration of the 660th anniversary of Amir Timur, or Tamerlane, <br>
     began on 18 October, Narodnoe slovo reported, as monitored by the BBC <br>
     on 21 October. Uzbek President Islam Karimov officially opened a <br>
     museum in Tashkent devoted to the Central Asian figure, noting that <br>
     "the civilized world has a proper appreciation of Tamerlane's undying <br>
     service to mankind." The ceremony included readings from the Koran, <br>
     blessings from honored elders, and a traditional plov (pilau) feast. <br>
     For the next month, similar celebrations will take place throughout <br>
     Uzbekistan. -- Roger Kangas<br>
      <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
