<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: OMRI--16 Oct 1996--MIXED RETURNS ON UZBEK HARVESTS</title>
<h1>OMRI--16 Oct 1996--MIXED RETURNS ON UZBEK HARVESTS</h1>
<i>eurasia@sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Wed, 16 Oct 96 11:40:53 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "OMRI--21 Oct 1996--PAKISTAN'S PRESIDENT VISITS UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--Oct 16 1996--UZBEK SOM IN TROUBLE?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     <br>
     <br>
     MIXED RETURNS ON UZBEK HARVESTS. The Uzbek government announced that <br>
     grain harvests are well below expectations for the second year in a <br>
     row, according to an 8 October Uzbek Radio report monitored by the <br>
     BBC. The 1996 harvest currently stands at 2,669,000 metric tons, well <br>
     below the target figure of 4.5 million tons. Only seven regions were <br>
     able to meet their quotas, with the rest blaming poor irrigation, bad <br>
     weather, and a lack of fertilizer for the shortfalls. At the same <br>
     time, the Central Council of the People's Democratic Party called on <br>
     Uzbek citizens to participate in the cotton harvest, which is expected <br>
     to be higher than last year (see OMRI Daily Digest, 15 October 1996). <br>
     Regional party leaders are even offering prizes for the most "active" <br>
     volunteer--a practice reminiscent of the Soviet era--Golos Uzbekistana <br>
     reported on 11 October. -- Roger Kangas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">arichter@sorosny.org: "OMRI--21 Oct 1996--PAKISTAN'S PRESIDENT VISITS UZBEKISTAN"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">eurasia@sorosny.org: "OMRI--Oct 16 1996--UZBEK SOM IN TROUBLE?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
