<title>OMRI and Other Excerpts for Uzbekistan: UZBEKISTAN RIGHTS CONFERENCE</title>
<h1>UZBEKISTAN RIGHTS CONFERENCE</h1>
<i>eurasia@mail.sorosny.org</i><br>
<i>Thu, 12 Sep 96 08:10:50 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="index.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="thread.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">eurasia@mail.sorosny.org: "OMRI--9 September 1996 -- GEORGIAN-UZBEK MILITARY COOPERATIO"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">tlankina@sorosny.org: "OMRI--9 September 96--UZBEKISTAN'S HUMAN RIGHT SOCIETY HOLDS"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DATE=9/11/96<br>
TYPE=CORRESPONDENT REPORT<br>
NUMBER=2-202952<br>
TITLE=UZBEKISTAN RIGHTS CONFERENCE (L-O)<br>
BYLINE=DOUGLAS BAKSHIAN<br>
DATELINE=TASHKENT<br>
CONTENT=<br>
VOICED AT:<br>
<p>
INTRO:  POLITICAL OBSERVERS SAY UZBEKISTAN TOOK A BIG STEP<br>
FORWARD WEDNESDAY AS A WELL KNOWN DISSIDENT ADDRESSED A HUMAN<br>
RIGHTS CONFERENCE ALONG WITH SENIOR GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS.<br>
ANALYSTS SAY THIS IS AN IMPORTANT MOVE IN A COUNTRY ATTEMPTING TO<br>
LIBERALIZE AFTER A LONG HISTORY OF AUTHORITARIAN RULE.  V-O-A<br>
CORRESPONDENT DOUGLAS BAKSHIAN IS FOLLOWING DEVELOPMENTS IN<br>
TASHKENT.<br>
<p>
TEXT:  THE CONFERENCE BEGAN WITH A WRITTEN STATEMENT FROM UZBEK<br>
PRESIDENT ISLAM KARIMOV, WHICH WAS READ BY THE COUNTRY'S FOREIGN<br>
MINISTER (ABDUL AZIZ KAMILOV).<br>
<p>
THE ANNOUNCEMENT SAID THE NATION HAD SUCCESSFULLY ACHIEVED<br>
ECONOMIC REFORMS AND WAS TURNING ITS ATTENTION TOWARD SPEEDING UP<br>
DEVELOPMENT OF THE POLITICAL SYSTEM.<br>
<p>
THE DOCUMENT SPOKE OF CREATING A MECHANISM FOR THE PROTECTION OF<br>
HUMAN RIGHTS AND FREEDOMS BY THE GOVERNMENT AND THE NEED TO<br>
SUPPORT PUBLIC ORGANIZATIONS ALSO DEALING WITH HUMAN RIGHTS.  THE<br>
STATEMENT SPOKE OF COOPERATING WITH INTERNATIONAL RIGHTS GROUPS.<br>
<p>
A SENIOR MEMBER OF UZBEKISTAN'S JUDICIARY SAID THE NATION IS<br>
DEEPENING THE PROCESS OF DEMOCRATIC REFORMS AND THE COURTS<br>
REQUIRE A LOT OF WORK.  HE SAID SOMETIMES COURTS FOCUS ON<br>
PUNISHMENT BUT  NOT  ON PROTECTION OF INDIVIDUALS.<br>
<p>
ABDUMANOV PULATOV, A WELL KNOWN DISSIDENT WHO RECENTLY CAME BACK<br>
TO UZBEKISTAN AFTER MORE THAN THREE YEARS IN EXILE, ALSO SPOKE.<br>
HE SAID HIS RETURN ALONE SHOWS LIMITED BUT POSITIVE CHANGES IN<br>
HUMAN RIGHTS, BUT HE SAID MANY PROBLEMS REMAIN AND THEY SHOULD BE<br>
SOLVED GRADUALLY.<br>
<p>
THE SON OF A RELIGIOUS LEADER ALSO ADDRESSED THE CONFERENCE.<br>
ABDU KUDUZ SAID HE COULD  NOT  BELIEVE THAT SUCH A HUMAN RIGHTS<br>
SEMINAR COULD TAKE PLACE IN UZBEKISTAN.  HE SPOKE OF THE<br>
DISAPPEARANCE OF HIS FATHER, A WELL KNOWN IMAM IN THE ANDIJAN<br>
REGION OF THE COUNTRY.<br>
<p>
A WESTERN HUMAN RIGHTS OFFICIAL SAID THE MERE TESTIMONY OF SUCH<br>
INDIVIDUALS BEFORE A RIGHTS FORUM IN UZBEKISTAN IS A BIG STEP<br>
FORWARD FOR THE COUNTRY.  HE SAID THIS IS THE FIRST TIME IN YEARS<br>
THAT SUCH PEOPLE WOULD EVEN BE ALLOWED TO OPEN THEIR MOUTHS IN<br>
PUBLIC.<br>
<p>
OBSERVERS SAY UZBEK PRESIDENT KARIMOV HAS RECENTLY MADE MOVES<br>
TOWARDS LIBERALIZATION AFTER RULING THE COUNTRY WITH AN IRON HAND<br>
SINCE INDEPENDENCE FIVE YEARS AGO.  THE PRESIDENT INVITED MR.<br>
PULATOV BACK TO UZBEKISTAN AFTER MEETING HIM IN THE UNITED STATES<br>
SEVERAL MONTHS AGO.  IN RECENT STATEMENTS MR. KARIMOV HAS SPOKEN<br>
REPEATEDLY OF THE NEED TO PROTECT HUMAN RIGHTS AND MAKE REFORMS.<br>
<p>
THE THREE-DAY CONFERENCE IS BEING HELD BY THE ORGANIZATION FOR<br>
SECURITY AND COOPERATION IN EUROPE IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE UZBEK<br>
GOVERNMENT.  REPRESENTATIVES OF FOUR OTHER CENTRAL ASIAN NATIONS,<br>
KYRGYZSTAN, KAZAKHSTAN, TAJIKISTAN AND TURKMENISTAN ARE TAKING<br>
PART.  (SIGNED)<br>
<p>
NEB / DB / BD / JCF<br>
<p>
11-Sep-96 1:13 PM EDT (1713 UTC)<br>
NNNN<br>
<p>
Source: Voice of America<br>
.<br>
<p>
