<HR>
<A NAME="m.+m.+jones"><B>M. M. Jones</B></A><BR>
<I>m.m.jones@worldnet.att.net</I><BR>
USA	 - none<BR>
 - none<BR>
EDUCATION	 - N/A
<BR>
ARTICLE	 - New York Times 12/17/96
<BR>
Programs of Interest:  PROJECT ON DEATH IN AMERICA :<BR>
<BR>
<PRE>I am interested in the Project on Death in America, because 
of my concern about the push for older, sick people to end 
their lives prematurely, either through active means or 
through making it hard for them to get treatment.
  
Younger people, including medical personnel, are beginning to 
look at the right to die as the duty to die.  The refusal of 
heroic medical treatment by older people is seen as a decision 
they owe to the rest of society.

I think life is each person's most important possession, and 
the right to die implies an equally strong, if not stronger, 
right to live.  Many people, for various reasons, may choose 
not to prolong their lives with medical treatment when faced 
with a terminal illness.  But it should be possible for those 
who opt to cling to every bit of life, even in the face of 
pain and severe disability, to get unquestioned backing from 
some group or organization.  This kind of support is now hard 
to find in the churches (particularly among the clergy); and 
it is disappearing in the government, where it is being eroded
by the medical community.  

This is a very recent development.  It could not be found 15 
years ago, at least not in community hospitals.</PRE>
Signed on: Tue Dec 17 08:23:48 EST 1996<BR>

