Programs of Interest:  BURMA PROJECT :<BR>
<BR>
South East Asian nations & Middle East<BR>
<PRE>Excellent web site for monitoring the latest news on Burma. 
However, there's too much rhetoric than 
actual news. 
My friends and family were among the tens 
of thousands of Burmese who fled the country during the
26-year revolution (1962-1988). The fleeing Burmese lost
everything: money, property, friends, a whole way of life,
a country. Australia alone gave refuge to 200,000 Burmese
during the dark Burmese days.
While all these terrible tragedies were unfolding in Burma, 
the silence from the West (for 26 tortuous years) was, 
unfortunately, deafening.
I have just finished researching  and am still compiling
materials  for a book on Burma's political and economic
history. The main focus would be on the Marxist 
socialist revolution which ended in turmoil in 1988. 
It is a tragedy that Burmese history has been fast-forwarded 
since.   I feel very strongly about this period  
the darkest in modern Burmese history  because there are 
those who pretend as if "nothing happened."
As the (West)German President Weizsaecker said in 1985:...
"whoever is not ready to tackle his own history will not
understand where he stands today and why. Whoever denies
the past runs the risk of repeating it."
I feel that this is exactly what is happening today: 
total denial of the past. 
As such I have decded to write this book. Those Burmese who 
wish to share their experience may contact me at the
following address:
Omar Farouk @ Richard Mookerdum
PO Box 102
Latham, Canberra ACT 2615
Australia.  Phone&Fax: +616 278 3093.

P.S. I hope that Burma Project would help convey this
message to my fellow Burmese compatriots.  Many thanks.
          


  
 </PRE>
Signed on: Sat Nov  9 05:13:01 EST 1996<BR>

