<A NAME="irving+silver"><B>Irving Silver</B></A><BR>
<I>irvsilv@aol.com</I><BR>
USA	 - B'nai B'rith Center For Public Policy<BR>
 - Past Chm<BR>
NGO	 - service org
<BR>
SEARCH ENGINE	 - NY Times for 10-1-96 on AOL
<BR>
Programs of Interest:  REGIONAL PUBLISHING PROGRAM :<BR>
<BR>
Countries of Interest:  SLOVAKIA :<BR>
<PRE>Philanthropist Pledges Aid to Immigrants
By ERIC SCHMITT/ October 1, 1996/ The New York Times

WASHINGTONGeorge Soros, the Hungarian-born philanthropist and international financier, said Monday he would give $50 million to assist legal immigrants in the United States. 
Soros said he was creating the new charity in response to the recently enacted welfare law that greatly restricts public benefits like food stamps and Supplemental Security Income for legal immigrants. 
"I am appalled by Congress recent action to deny vital public assistance to non-citizens who are lawfully resident in this country," Soros, a naturalized U.S. citizen, said at a news conference. 
"This is a clear-cut case of injustice and is contrary to this countrys proud tradition of welcoming immigrants," he said. Soros emigrated to England from Hungary in 1947, and to the United States in 1956. 
The money will go largely to pay for the costs of immigrants applying to become naturalized U.S. citizens, and to assist local and community organizations that provide English-language classes and other aid to immigrants. 
More than 1.1 million immigrants have become naturalized citizens this year, and federal officials expect the harsh provisions in the welfare bill to push equally large numbers of legal immigrants toward citizenship in the next few years. 
The charity, called the Emma Lazarus Fund after the poet whose words are inscribed on the Statue of Liberty, will also support organizations conducting legal or educational efforts on the behalf of immigrants. 
Immigrant-rights groups expressed astonishment Monday at Soros new project. 
"Were thrilled," said Donald Kerwin, chief operating officer for Catholic Legal Immigration Network, a public-interest organization based in Washington. "This is probably more money in a given year than all the foundations and state bar associations give out. Its really shocking." 
The new charity is an offshoot of the Open Society Institute and other Soros philanthropies, which spent $350 million in 1995 mostly in countries undergoing the transition to democratic regimes. 
In addition, Soros was one of the early proponents of lifting the siege of Sarajevo during the Bosnian war. He proposed a $50 million aid plan to Bosnia in 1993, but suspended the offer when logistical details bogged down in bickering. 
More recently, Soros has given out or pledged nearly $15 million to help change the nations drug policy. For example, Soros has advocated legalizing the medical use of marijuana, and has been critical of efforts to treat drug use as a crime rather than a medical problem. 
Other Places of Interest on the Web
Soros Foundations Network  
http://www.soros.org/  


</PRE>
Signed on: Wed Oct  2 01:03:07 EDT 1996<BR>

