<PRE>I'm happy I found this site!  I spent some time yesterday
looking for the Emma Lazarus Fund (I was trying Foundation
instead of Fund) through a general search and couldn't find
it.  I had just seen Mr. Soros on the evening news making
his announcement about it.  This is the first I'd ever heard
of Mr. Soros and the incredibily generous foundations he's
been establishing and funding over the years.  It's such 
important work and so heartwarming to know all the good he's
doing in giving back what he's been given!  

One of the programs I work for trains teachers for Second
Language Education and helps prepare them for E.S.L. state
certification.  There is such a need for it in this area, 
with more and more people immigrating hear from Russia, Asia,
and Puerto Rico, not to mention various other countries.  
We only have 1 full-time faculty member to oversee the whole
operation here.  She has done an enormous amount of work in 
the last few years to see that as many teachers, graduate 
students, etc., and getting the training and experience they
need to meet the challenges that are faced here, as well as
many students coming from other countries to obtain graduate
degrees, which will enable them to go back to their home 
countries and help their people back there with English.  We
experienced many financial cuts over the years, and School 
is always looking for funds to enable faculty and students
to do all they possibly can to train teachers, as well as 
serve the community directly by having student teachers do
direct instruction for ESL. 

We also have a Bilingual Education component in this School,
as well as Reading & Writing, Mulitcultural Education, 
Native American/Indigenous Education, International 
Education, and a number of other programs.

Any more information you can provide that I could
pass on the faculty and graduate students for grantwriting
would be grately appreciated!  Thanks, and keep up the good
work!  Sincerely, Donna M. Brouillet, School of Education, 
University of Massachusetts, 107 Furcolo Hall, Amherst, MA
01003.

</PRE>
