<html>  
<head>  
<title>CEE Harm Reduction Initiatives...(The Lindesmith Center)</title>  
</head>  
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000">  
<center><h4>THE LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center>  
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#"></center><br> <h2><center>Harm Reduction 
Initiatives as Drug Policy Alternatives</center></h2>  
<hr> 
<p> 
<h3>Purpose:</h3> 
To support local, national, or regional initiatives in Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet 
Union that address local drug problems through innovative measures based upon "harm reduction" 
approaches and practices.  
<p> 
<h3>The Harm Reduction Philosophy:</h3> 
The Lindesmith Center would like to explain that Harm Reduction is an alternative approach to drug policy 
and treatment, which requires a certain programmatic approach.  Developing drug treatment services can 
be compared to building a pyramid. The mistake often made in the West is that we only built the top of the 
pyramid, offering services requiring abstinence, a commitment most drug users are not able or willing to 
make. Even when free of charge, those services only reach 5-10% of the population, while drop-out and 
relapse are very high. The HIV/AIDS epidemic painfully elucidated our failure to contact a majority of 
injecting drug users (IDUs).  
<p> 
The concept of Harm Reduction entails "the whole pyramid," providing a wide range of services to drug 
users.  When building a pyramid, or any other construction project for that matter, one generally starts at its 
base. In developing drug treatment this translates into a priority on basic, "low threshold" services, aimed 
at improving health and social well-being in a step-wise process, acknowledging any positive change as an 
improvement. Through outreach work, syringe exchange, methadone maintenance, and emergency medical 
care, Harm Reduction services reach 70-80% of drug addicts.  While many of you are familiar with the 
Harm Reduction philosophy, we would like to restate the notion that Harm Reduction does not exclude 
abstinence, but rather it is perceived as one among a wide range of possible preventions. 
<p> 
While Harm Reduction has only been applied within the field of drug policy and treatment for about ten 
years, it is an expression of a much broader social-organizational principle with many mainstream 
applications.  In fact, it is one of the principle models of organization in our society. Seat belts, anti lock 
brakes, airbags, stop lights and traffic regulations are, for example, all part of a well accepted Harm 
Reduction policy to reduce the (considerable) harm from motorized transportation. 
<p> 
<h3>Beneficiary Countries to Date:</h3>
(<i>click on any of the countries below for more information</i>)
<p>
<table border=0>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/bulgaria.html"><b>Bulgaria</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/macedon.html"><b>Macedonia</b></a></td></tr>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/croatia.html"><b>Croatia</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/poland.html"><b>Poland</b></a></td></tr>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/czech.html"><b>Czech R.</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/russia.html"><b>Russia</b></a></td></tr>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/hungary.html"><b>Hungary</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/slovakia.html"><b>Slovakia</a></td></tr>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/latvia.html"><b>Latvia</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/slovenia.html"><b>Slovenia</a></td></tr>
<tr><td align=left width=80><a href="http://www.soros.org/lithuan.html"><b>Lithuania</b></a></td><td align=left><a href="http://www.soros.org/ukraine.html"><b>Ukraine</a></td></tr>
</table> 
<p> 
<h3>Background:</h3> 
Due to the concern that repressive drug policies may become the dominant way of addressing drug 
problems in Central and Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union, the Regional Medical Program and 
The Lindesmith Center of the Open Society Institute sponsored a meeting of 35 experts mostly from CEE 
concomitantly with the Sixth International Conference on the Reduction of Drug Related Harm, held in 
Florence in March of 1995. An outcome of this meeting was the creation of the new regional program 
described here. 
<p> 
<h3>Developments in 1995-1996:</h3> 
The Harm Reduction Initiatives program, a joint collaboration of the Regional Medical Program, The 
Lindesmith Center and  National Soros Foundations, made available in 1995 the sum of $500,000 to 
applicants interested in organizing innovative harm reduction approaches. Out of 140 applications received 
via participating National Soros Foundations, requesting over $4 million in funding, 30 grants were made 
in 1995, primarily to programs that offer basic "low threshold" services to drug users and projects that 
promote a harm reduction approach to drug use and services. These include: outreach efforts to improve 
the health and well-being of illicit drug-users; methadone and other drug substitution-oriented treatment 
programs; provision and exchange of sterile syringes; training of medical, public health and social workers, 
and criminal justice personnel in harm reduction approaches; attendance at international conferences on 
related topics, evaluation of local drug problems and policies by experts; purchase, translation, publication 
and distribution of harm reduction materials; internet connection; and drug treatment programs that seek to 
reduce drug use and the attendant harms instead of focusing entirely on abstinence from drugs. Other 
measures include training and education programs and provision and exchange of information on drug use, 
abuse, and treatment. 
<p> 
<a href="ceempp.html"><b><i>The Model Project Program</i></b></a><br> 
Of the 30 grants allocated, thirteen projects (four methadone maintenance programs and nine needle 
exchange/outreach programs) have been selected as model projects for the region.  As model projects, 
these programs have been partnered with established service organizations from Western Europe and the 
U.S. (mirror organizations), which will provide targeted programmatic support and ongoing 
communication with the model projects.  In March, 1996, the program held a workshop in Budapest 
designed to bring together international professionals involved in drug treatment and participants of the 
Model Project Program to share information and experiences, with the specific goal of providing support to 
model projects.  Since March, staff workers from the model projects and mirror organizations have been 
visiting their partner organizations to provide programmatic and organizational training to the model 
projects.  Our hope is that in the future the model projects will be able to work independently with other 
programs in their region. 
<p> 
<h3>Current Developments and Further Plans for 1996-1997:</h3> 
<i>Harm Reduction Training</i><br> 
In response to several applications requesting harm reduction training, the Harm Reduction Initiatives 
program has organized a needle exchange and outreach training program to take place during July and 
August, 1996, in four different regions in Central and East Europe in cooperation with the National Soros 
Foundations and colleagues from the region.  Outside consultants have developed a four-day training 
module on outreach work designed to train up to 50 individuals per location in a harm reduction approach 
to working with drug users. The program plans additional training programs for the end of 1996 and in 
1997. 
<p> 
<i>Conferences</i><br>
The program is collaborating with colleagues and National Soros Foundations in Russia, Poland, 
Macedonia, Latvia and Lithuania to support regional conferences that address harm reduction approaches 
to drug use and drug services.  The conferences will address a wide range of issues of interest to medical 
providers, policy makers, law enforcement personnel, social workers, service providers, and drug users. 
<p> 
Pending the review of the grants given in 1995, consideration will be given to the possibility of renewing 
funding, and offering this regional program to countries not presently participating. 
<p> 
<h3>Implementation/Management:</h3> 
The program is a collaborative effort of the Regional Medical Program and The Lindesmith Center of the 
Open Society Institute, and participating Soros National Foundations.  The NY office of OSI launched the 
program and designed the application forms. The National Foundations advertise the program and collect 
the application forms, which are sent to the offices of The Lindesmith Center with their recommendations. 
The Lindesmith Center reviews the applications and designates the successful applicants in consultation 
with the Regional Medical Program. 
<p> 
<b>Program Co-Chair:</b> Ethan Nadelmann (The Lindesmith Center)<br>
<b>Program Co-Chair:</b> Elizabeth Lorant (Regional Programs)<br> 
<b>Program Director:</b> Jean-Paul Grund (The Lindesmith Center)<br> 
<b>Program Coordinator:</b> Kate Blumenreich (The Lindesmith Center) 
 
<p>
<center>For more information on the <i>International Harm Reduction Development 
</i>programs,<br>
please email <A 
href="mailto:kblumenreich@sorosny.org"><b>kblumenreich@sorosny.org</b></A></center> 
<hr>  
<p>  
<center> 
<a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcintro.html"><img src=subbar.jpg alt="subject index"></a><a  
href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlcmain.html"><img src=hombar.jpg alt="tlc home"></a><a  
href="http://www.lindesmith.org/tlchot.html"><img src=hotbar.jpg alt="what's hot!"</a><br><a  
