<html> 
<head> 
<title>DPF Grants 1996 (The Lindesmith Center)</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="FFFFFF" link="006699" vlink="339999" text="000000"> 
<center><h4>THE LINDESMITH CENTER</h4></center> 
<center><img align=middle src=line.gif width=600 alt=#></center> <br> 
<center><h2>DRUG POLICY FOUNDATION</h2></center>
<Center><h2>Guidelines for Grants as of November, 1996</h2></center>
<p>
<hr>
<p>     
<h3>I. THE ORGANIZATION</h3>

The Drug Policy Foundation (DPF) is a non-profit, independent forum 
founded in 1986 to research and publicize alternatives to the war on 
drugs.  DPF believes that the nation should start viewing drug abuse more 
as a public health problem than a criminal justice problem, and should 
focus not on the unrealistic goal of eliminating drug use entirely but 
instead concentrate on reducing the harms associated with drug abuse.  DPF 
aims to change policies and attitudes that demonize addicts while doing 
nothing to reintegrate them into society.  Historically, DPF has focused 
primarily on public education, publishing books, reports, and newsletters, 
producing television programs and sponsoring conferences.  Recently, DPF 
has added a government affairs program to work for change at the federal, 
state and local levels.
<p>
In its nine years of operation, DPF has become the leading force for drug 
policy reform in the nation.  DPF's board includes doctors, policemen, 
mayors and federal judges; its conferences attract reformers from around 
the world, forging links among policymakers, academics, and service 
providers.  DPF membership now exceeds 20,000 paid supporters.
 <p>
<h3>II. GRANT PROGRAM OBJECTIVES</h3>     

The goal of the grant program is to advance drug policy reform, particularly in the United States.  Grants will be made to organizations and individuals to support:
<ul>
<li>Harm Reduction Programs, including but not limited to needle exchange.

<li>Advocacy Efforts that support drug policy reform.

<li>Public Education on drug policy reform issues.
</ul>
<p>

<h3>III. PRIORITIES FOR FUNDING</h3>
<ol>
<li><b>Harm Reduction Programs:</b>
<p>
Funds will be awarded to organizations seeking to work with drug abusers to improve their welfare; alleviate their physical, social or mental health problems; encourage non-coercive alternatives to incarceration; or reduce the harms of substance abuse using other creative strategies.
<p>
Grants should be significant enough to enable an organization to launch
a new program (including support of the planning phase), expand a successful program or help evaluate an existing program.  Ideally, the organization would also receive grants from other public or private sources.  In order to determine the effectiveness of initiatives funded under this category, organizations applying should, if possible, include an evaluation component with their proposal.  Organizations submitting applications for needle exchange program funding must include information on the legality of such activities in their state and locality, including information about court decisions, pending legal cases, the position of local law enforcement officials on needle exchange programs and state law.
<p>
DPF's purpose in funding direct services is strategic: to support programs that can create a "ripple effect" -- programs that by their example will advance the cause of harm reduction and facilitate the expansion of such programs.  Applicants should stress how their programs will win harm reduction new supporters and create a more hospitable climate for similar efforts in the future.
<p>
<li><b>Advocacy Efforts:</b><p>

To advance drug policy reform DPF will assist new or existing organizations looking to broaden the policy debate and amplify the voices of those advocating reform.  Applicants seeking funds to do advocacy work must be capable of accounting for these activities consistent with 501(c)(3) requirements.
<p>
Priority for advocacy-related grants will be given to proposals tied to specific reform activities and applicants who show how they will reach communities currently underrepresented in the reform movement.  Among the priority issue areas are state legislative reforms in methadone treatment, medical marijuana, syringe deregulation, needle exchange and criminal law.
<p>
<li><b>Drug Policy Education:</b><p>

Funds will be awarded to assist organizations in educating the public, professions, community groups and other important individuals and organizations in important drug policy reform issues.  Priority will be given to education efforts targeted to strategically important groups who have not previously been involved in the drug policy debate. Proposals should specify the groups or organizations to be targeted, the kind of education to be done, the issues on which the education will focus and the goal of such educational activities.
</ol>
<p>

<i>Proposals not readily falling into any of the three categories above should not be submitted without first discussing the project with DPF Grant Program staff (see below).  In particular, journalistic and academic projects will be supported only under exceptional circumstances.  While there are no formal limits on award levels, past grants have rarely exceeded $25,000.  Indirect costs, to a maximum of 10% of total salaries, may be included when the sponsoring institution is providing tangible support to the project.</i>
<p>
<h3>IV. APPLICATION INSTRUCTIONS</h3>

Proposals are currently reviewed two times a year.  To be reviewed in the Summer Round, proposals must be postmarked by May 1.  To be reviewed in the Winter Round, proposals must be postmarked by October 1.  This schedule is subject to change; please call to confirm deadlines before submitting.
<p>
Exceptions to these dates will only be made if:<p>
<ul><ul>
<li>the proposal is of an emergency nature;
<li>the need for the project was not apparent prior to the relevant due
date; and
<li>waiting until the subsequent grant period would render the proposal
moot.
</ul></ul>
<p>
All proposals and correspondence should be addressed to DPF's New York office.  When submitting proposals, please send two copies.  At least one of these copies should be submitted in a format that is easily re-produced.
<p>
<b>Proposals should include:</b>
<p>
<ol>
<li>A one-page proposal summary.  This summary must specify the
organization's 501(c)(3) status.  No application can be considered without this
summary, which should  be placed at the beginning of the application.  Summaries
exceeding one page cannot be accepted.
<li>Information on the history and purpose of the organization. (1 page)
<li>A description of the project, why it is needed, and what it hopes to
accomplish.
(3 pages)
<li>Plans for project evaluation and, if appropriate, dissemination. (1
page)
<li>A project budget, including a schedule of expenditures and a
narrative
description of each.
<li>An organizational budget, including a list of other pending grant
applications.
<li>An IRS determination letter (if the applicant is a 501(c)(3)
organization).
</ol>
<p>
The above materials, excluding the IRS determination letter and budget
materials, should not exceed six pages.  Additional materials, such as press clippings and videotapes, are encouraged and should be submitted, if possible, with the initial proposal.

<p>
<b>Should you require additional information, please contact:</b>
<p>
Charles Honig<br>
Grant Coordinator<br>
The Drug Policy Foundation<br>
888 Seventh Avenue, 27th floor<br>
New York, NY  10106<br>
(212) 307-5630<br>
<a href="mailto:honig@dpf.org"><b>honig@dpf.org</b></a>
 
<p> 
<hr> 
